<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-634-867  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 634 867.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Wall Street Computer Review  Nov 1990 v8 n2 p55(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software simplifies asset allocation strategies.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bobseine, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The numerous new types of securities, the trend to internationalinvesting and the rise of modern portfolio theory which assessesand invests in markets rather than individual securities aredriving the growth in the use of asset allocation software.andP;  Assetallocation involves investing in mixed classes of securitieswithin the constraints of a desired rate of return offset againsta level of risk tolerance.andP;  There are three approaches: strategicallocation, which employs historical data and projects of earningsto forecast how classes of securities will perform over time;tactical asset allocation which uses periodic changes in the mixof securities to achieve better performance; and dynamic assetallocation, which reflects changes in an investor's situation tomaintaining a balance between investor goals and policies and theallocation process.andP;  Numerous asset allocation products arebriefly discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     InvestmentsFinancial SoftwareUtilizationCapital InvestmentCapital AssetFinancial Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>